This problem is specifically related to LeetCode Problem 238. Below are the two code snippets I&#39;ve been working with:

Code Snippet 1 (2 Loops) (My Code):

```
public int[] productExceptSelf(int[] nums) {
    int[] result = new int[nums.length];
    result[0] = 1;

    for(int i = 0; i &lt; nums.length - 1; i++){
        result[i+1] = nums[i] * result[i];
    }

    int product = 1;
    for(int i = nums.length - 1; i &gt; 0; i--){
        result[i-1] = nums[i] * result[i - 1] * product;
        product = product * nums[i];
    }

    return result;
}

```

Code Snippet 2 (3 Loops) (Code that takes 1ms):

```
public int[] productExceptSelf(int[] nums) {
    int res[] = new int[nums.length];
    
    for(int num: nums) {
        num = 1;
    }

    int prefix = 1;
    for(int i=0; i&lt;nums.length; i++) {
        res[i] = prefix;
        prefix *= nums[i];
    }
    int postfix = 1;
    for(int i=nums.length-1; i&gt;=0; i--) {
        res[i] *= postfix;
        postfix *= nums[i];
    }

    return res;
}

```



Both code snippets have an O(n) time complexity and solve the same problem, which makes the performance difference even more intriguing.

