To improve the time complexity of your code, you can use a binary search approach to find the valid positions for x. This will significantly reduce the time complexity from O(n^2) to O(n * log(m)) where n is the size of the houses array and m is the range of x-coordinates to check (which is 2 * 10^9 in your case).

    public static void main(String[] args) {
    System.out.println(solve(Arrays.asList(2, 0, 3, -4), 22));
    }
    
    public static int solve(List&lt;Integer&gt; houses, long distance) {
        int n = houses.size();
        Collections.sort(houses);
        int first = houses.get(0), last = houses.get(n - 1);
        long leftMax = first - distance, rightMax = last + distance;
    
        int result = 0;
        for (long i = -1000000000; i &lt;= 1000000000; i++) { // Adjust this range based on constraints
            long temp = 0;
            for (int p : houses) {
                temp += 2 * Math.abs(p - i);
                if (temp &gt; distance) {
                    break;
                }
            }
            if (temp &lt;= distance) {
                System.out.print(i + &quot; &quot;);
                result++;
            }
        }
        System.out.println();
        return result;
    }

In this code, we iterate through the x-coordinates in the range [-10^9, 10^9] using a loop. For each x-coordinate, we calculate the total distance to all houses and check if it&#39;s within the given distance limit. If it is, we print the valid x-coordinate and increment the result count. The binary search approach is not necessary here because the range of x-coordinates to check is relatively small (2 * 10^9), so a linear search is efficient enough.

Keep in mind that the range of x-coordinates to check can be adjusted based on the constraints of your problem. If the range is too large, you might want to partition the range into smaller chunks and apply binary search within each chunk for further optimization.

**Edit**

You can optimize the solution by narrowing down the search range based on the first and last house positions.

Here&#39;s an optimized version of solve function:

    public static int solve(List&lt;Integer&gt; houses, long distance) {
        int n = houses.size();
        Collections.sort(houses);
        int first = houses.get(0), last = houses.get(n - 1);
        long leftMax = first - distance, rightMax = last + distance;
    
        int result = 0;
        for (long i = leftMax; i &lt;= rightMax; i++) {
            long temp = 0;
            for (int p : houses) {
                temp += 2 * Math.abs(p - i);
                if (temp &gt; distance) {
                    break;
                }
            }
            if (temp &lt;= distance) {
                System.out.print(i + &quot; &quot;);
                result++;
            }
        }
        System.out.println();
        return result;
    }

Your approach is correct: sorting the houses based on the x-coordinate will indeed lead to the house with the minimum sum of distances being near the median index. When you move away from this point to the left or right, the sum of distances increases due to the increasing number of houses that are farther away compared to those closer.

Therefore, the problem becomes quite straightforward: you only need to find the range of houses corresponding to the median index, and then expand it as much as possible to both sides, as all the houses within this range will satisfy the target.

Regarding the &quot;expansion&quot; part, considering the wide range of coordinates, directly enumerating them is not wise. However, based on the observations above, you&#39;ll notice a property: let `f(x)` be the sum of distances from point x to all houses. Then, `f(x)` forms a unimodal function (its minimum value is near the median-indexed house). Within this monotonically increasing range, you can use binary search to speed up the process.

For this code, the complexity of sorting is `O(nlogn)`, and the binary search for the answer (expanding the range) has a complexity of $O(nlogM)$, where `M` is the range of x-coordinates.

