A CSR; [Permit additional statements before this/super in constructors](https://bugs.openjdk.org/browse/JDK-8302041) has now been approved for Java 22, which is scheduled for release in March 2024. 

---

It most likely will become possible to do this. Currently, the call to the super-constructor must be the first statement in a constructor. There is a JEP draft, named [_Statements before super()_](https://openjdk.org/jeps/8300786) that seeks to change this. This particular JEP draft was opened in January of 2023, however, the discussion has been ongoing for a few years. It&#39;s a continuation of [this issue](https://bugs.openjdk.org/browse/JDK-8194743) from 2018, opened by Brian Goetz, the lead architect of Java, so there&#39;s reason to believe that this will go through now that somebody has taken the time to work on it.

A [compiler implementation for this change](https://bugs.openjdk.org/browse/JDK-8302038) has already been completed. Once the JLS has been updated, one can freely use statements before the call to the super-constructor, except `try {} catch {}`, as it was decided to take a conservative approach at this.

So this will be possible:
```java
class Foo extends Bar {

    Foo() {
        System.out.println(&quot;Before super&quot;);
        super();
        System.out.println(&quot;After super&quot;);
    }
}
```

